body:
@cemo partly because use of local timezone is mostly an anti-pattern (that is, developers use it without realizing, causing issues). And this because similar to "default encoding" it is often somewhat arbitrary what the timezone might be. I guess this is just one argument in two parts...
But basically use of local timezones seemed to me to be a source of many kinds of preventable problems.

So, to me it is similar to "why default to UTF-8 instead of platform default encoding", although it is not exactly the same thing (because JSON mandates UTF-8 as default etc).

issue.body:
### Search before asking

- [X] I searched in the [issues](https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/issues) and found nothing similar.

### Describe the bug

When `DeserializationFeature.ADJUST_DATES_TO_CONTEXT_TIME_ZONE` is enabled and a textual `OffsetDateTime` representation is deserialized, it is adjusted to contextual `TimeZone`. Nice feature by the way.

But if no contextual `TimeZone` is set, it is always adapted to `UTC` which IMHO is a bug. I would rather expect the input to be left as it is, as there is no context regarding the time zone and no indication that a specific time zone should be adopted at all.

### Version Information

2.15.2

### Reproduction

```java
@Test
void offsetDateTimeBackToBack() throws IOException {
	final ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper()
			.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule())
			// .disable(DeserializationFeature.ADJUST_DATES_TO_CONTEXT_TIME_ZONE)
			.disable(SerializationFeature.WRITE_DATES_AS_TIMESTAMPS);
	final OffsetDateTime odt = OffsetDateTime.ofInstant(Instant.now(), ZoneId.of("America/New_York"));
	final OffsetDateTime back = objectMapper.readValue(objectMapper.writeValueAsString(odt), OffsetDateTime.class);
	assertEquals(odt, back);
}
``` 


### Additional context

Edit: Looking at #915, I can follow the reasoning given there falling back to `UTC` implicitly as a default state. I can easily deactivate the feature, I just stumbled across it because it is activated by default. So, if your response is 'works as designed', I am fine with that.
